at least 220,000 lives since the
1960s, and

10:45.745 --> 10:50.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
displaced millions more, but it
still needed
ratification.

10:50.350 --> 10:55.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After Sunday's rejection,
President Juan Manuel
Santos and the top FARC
commander appealed

10:55.255 --> 10:57.090 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for calm.

10:57.123 --> 10:59.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS, Colombian
President (through
translator): I call on those who
decided to

10:59.092 --> 11:02.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or not to support the agreement
to end the
conflict with the FARC.

11:02.862 --> 11:07.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now we are all together, going
to decide between
the path that we should take so
that peace

11:07.400 --> 11:08.368 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is possible.

11:08.401 --> 11:10.203 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I will not give up.

11:10.236 --> 11:14.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIMOCHENKO, FARC Leader (through
translator):
The FARC maintains its
willingness for peace

11:15.008 --> 11:20.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and reiterates its position to
use only words
as weapons to work towards the
future.

11:20.146 --> 11:24.751 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Colombian people who dream
of peace, you
can count on us.

11:24.784 --> 11:26.553 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Peace will win out.

11:26.586 --> 11:30.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Even former
President Alvaro
Uribe, a leader of the no
campaign, warned

11:30.924 --> 11:32.525 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
against reprisals.

11:32.559 --> 11:36.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALVARO URIBE, Former Colombian
President (through
translator): We all want peace.

11:36.296 --> 11:37.997 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Nobody wants violence.

11:38.031 --> 11:42.302 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We ask that the FARC are
protected and that
all crimes, including drug
trafficking and

11:42.335 --> 11:44.203 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
extortion, are stopped.

11:44.237 --> 11:48.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The United
States had backed
the accord, and, today, a White
House spokesman

11:48.308 --> 11:50.009 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
voiced hope.

11:50.043 --> 11:52.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSH EARNEST, White House Press
Secretary:
The good news is that all sides
including

11:52.345 --> 12:00.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the voters, I think, are still
focused on
trying to reach this negotiated
peace, and

12:00.386 --> 12:03.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that certainly is within the
national security
interests of the United States
to end this

12:03.623 --> 12:08.628 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
war, and we are going to
encourage all sides
to pursue that peace.

12:08.661 --> 12:14.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: For now, a
cease-fire remains
in effect, as negotiators ponder
the way forward.

12:14.701 --> 12:18.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To help us understand the future
of this peace
process, we're joined now by
someone intimately

12:18.871 --> 12:21.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
involved in securing the deal in
the first
place.

12:21.975 --> 12:25.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Bernard Aronson is the U.S.
special envoy
for talks between the Colombian
government

12:26.012 --> 12:27.180 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and the FARC rebels.

12:27.213 --> 12:28.147 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Welcome.

12:28.181 --> 12:30.450 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Fifty years of fighting.

12:30.483 --> 12:34.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hundreds of thousands of people
have been
killed, millions of people
pushed out of their

12:34.854 --> 12:35.955 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
homes.

12:35.989 --> 12:38.358 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why did voters reject this peace
plan?

12:38.391 --> 12:40.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BERNARD ARONSON, U.S. Special
Envoy for the
Colombian Peace Process: Well, I
think the

12:40.226 --> 12:44.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
woman who spoke about it in your
introduction
spoke for a lot of Colombians,
which is they

12:45.031 --> 12:49.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have suffered enormously, they
have been victimized,
they're bitter about that,
rightfully so,

12:49.969 --> 12:53.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and they felt the FARC got off
too easy in
this peace accord.

12:53.573 --> 12:56.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whether that's true or not is up
to debate,
but many Colombians felt that
way and they

12:56.876 --> 13:01.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
turned out, and, by a very small
majority,
rejected the accord.

13:01.714 --> 13:06.519 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: A very, very
small majority,
I mean, 50 to 49, almost.

13:06.552 --> 13:08.354 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Pick up that idea, though.

13:08.388 --> 13:14.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The argument that many of them
made is that
the FARC were involved in drug
trafficking,

13:14.060 --> 13:20.099 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
killings, kidnappings,
extortion, and to them
this deal felt like the FARC was
able to walk

13:20.133 --> 13:21.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
away scot-free.

13:21.134 --> 13:22.669 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is that a legitimate criticism?

13:22.702 --> 13:25.605 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BERNARD ARONSON: It isn't true
that they were
going to wake away scot-free.

13:25.638 --> 13:30.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What the agreement did was set
up a system
of justice called transitional
justice.

13:30.810 --> 13:36.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All the FARC members who were
accused of war
crimes, atrocities or atrocities
or violations

13:36.215 --> 13:40.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of international human rights
had to go before
these tribunals, confess all of
their crimes,

13:41.020 --> 13:45.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all their criminal activity,
give up any gains
they made from it, and then
subject themselves

13:45.892 --> 13:50.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to sanctions by the court, which
included
restrictions on liberty, though
maybe not

13:50.530 --> 13:54.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
prison, per se, and some kind of
sanction
of work.

13:54.701 --> 13:59.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have been sentenced to
spend five or
eight years removing land mines.

13:59.305 --> 14:05.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the people in Colombia whose
family were
kidnapped and who were killed or
driven off

14:05.445 --> 14:10.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their land, and they felt that
that wasn't
an appropriate punishment.

14:10.183 --> 14:13.953 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And that's part of the
discussion that has
to go forward now between the
government and

14:13.986 --> 14:15.188 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the opposition.

14:15.221 --> 14:17.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Well, what
does happen at
this point?

14:17.090 --> 14:22.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, before this vote was
held, the government
said if the vote goes no, we're
not coming

14:22.128 --> 14:23.463 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
back to the negotiating table.

14:23.496 --> 14:25.331 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The FARC said the same thing.

14:25.364 --> 14:27.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, where does the leave the
peace process?

14:27.166 --> 14:29.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BERNARD ARONSON: Well, but you
just heard
President Santos, in fact, say,
they are going

14:29.769 --> 14:31.404 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to try to renegotiate.

14:31.437 --> 14:35.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think what he wants to do, and
what he's
doing correctly, is try to reach
out to a

14:35.708 --> 14:40.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
broad spectrum of Colombian
political leadership,
including the no campaign, which
obviously

14:40.747 --> 14:45.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has to have a seat at the table
now, and see
if they can come up with some
new consensus

14:45.885 --> 14:48.154 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that they can start to discuss
with the FARC.

14:48.187 --> 14:51.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whether they will get there or
not is an open
question, but it's certainly
worth an effort.

14:51.691 --> 14:55.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this president has been
pretty relentless
in his pursuit of peace.

14:55.061 --> 14:57.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But do you
think the FARC
-- and you know many of these
leaders.

14:57.997 --> 15:00.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have worked with them
intimately over
the years.

15:00.333 --> 15:04.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do you think they are going to
tolerate a
further conversation where all
of a sudden

15:04.537 --> 15:09.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the government says, I know we
had a deal,
but now we have a new deal to
work out and

15:09.142 --> 15:11.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you guys are going to have to be
punished
more severely?

15:11.043 --> 15:12.011 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BERNARD ARONSON: Right.

15:12.044 --> 15:13.980 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not an easy sell.

15:14.013 --> 15:18.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the other hand, if the
opposition can be
brought into the deal so that
there is a national

15:18.951 --> 15:24.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
consensus behind it, that's good
for the peace
process, it's good for the FARC,
because,

15:24.123 --> 15:28.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with a country as divided as
Colombia is today,
to go forward with the
agreement, you would

15:28.528 --> 15:30.797 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
have made it a political
football for the
opposition.

15:30.830 --> 15:33.232 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It could be obstructed and torn
apart.

15:33.266 --> 15:37.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this way, the hope is -- and
it's a hope
at this point -- is that you can
create a

15:37.303 --> 15:41.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
national consensus which will be
enduring
and will unite the country.

15:41.073 --> 15:45.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Let's say that
it does forward
and there is some sort of
process reignited.

15:45.912 --> 15:51.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the things I know that
was an issue
at this was the FARC rebels to
disarm and

15:51.250 --> 15:54.987 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some of their soldiers would
then be reintegrated
into Colombian society.

15:55.021 --> 15:57.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My understanding is, many of
these are very,
very young people.

15:57.924 --> 16:03.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How does someone who's lived
their entire
life as a guerrilla soldier
suddenly put down

16:03.229 --> 16:05.765 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
arms and reintegrate into
society?

16:05.798 --> 16:09.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BERNARD ARONSON: Well, Colombia
actually has
a long history over the last 20
or 30 years

16:09.168 --> 16:12.171 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of reintegrating and
demobilizing guerrilla
forces.

16:12.205 --> 16:16.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what they do is a very sort
of systematic
approach with a presidential
institute.

16:16.142 --> 16:19.679 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They teach these young fighters
to read and
write, if they're not literate.

16:19.712 --> 16:21.013 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They teach them a job skill.

16:21.047 --> 16:23.516 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They reunite them with their
families.

16:23.549 --> 16:24.650 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They provide housing.

16:24.684 --> 16:27.787 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They often provide direct entree
to a job
opportunity.

16:27.820 --> 16:33.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not 100 percent foolproof,
but they actually
have a pretty good track record
of demobilizing

16:33.159 --> 16:34.994 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
guerrilla forces.

16:35.027 --> 16:38.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You are
someone who's worked
in this region for decades and
you know the

16:38.664 --> 16:40.499 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
players involved intimately.

16:40.533 --> 16:45.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, in the light of this
vote, do you have
any sense of hope that this is a
chance that

16:45.304 --> 16:48.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this is going to be restarted in
a meaningful
way?

16:48.407 --> 16:52.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BERNARD ARONSON: Colombians on
the yes vote
and the Colombians on the no
vote want peace.

16:52.945 --> 16:54.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't want to go back to
war.

16:54.313 --> 16:56.082 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They want a negotiated
settlement.

16:56.115 --> 17:01.821 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, I don't think it's
impossible the Colombians
can come together on a new
consensus.

17:01.854 --> 17:06.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Getting the FARC to give up what
they had
and go to a different set of
agreements is

17:06.759 --> 17:09.762 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not going to be easy, but they
don't have
other options either.

17:09.795 --> 17:13.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They don't want to go back to
war, and war
is not an option for them.

17:13.366 --> 17:19.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So this is an uphill fight, but
getting to
the peace accords was a very
long and torturous

17:19.305 --> 17:20.273 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
process.

17:20.306 --> 17:21.574 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, this is well worth the
effort.

17:21.607 --> 17:23.242 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
President Santos wants to do
this.

17:23.276 --> 17:25.278 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The United States obviously
support him.

17:25.311 --> 17:28.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Bernard Aronson,
thank you very much for being
here.

17:28.114 --> 17:33.719 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BERNARD ARONSON: Thank you.

17:33.753 --> 17:48.601 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now the first of
three reports
this week on the fight for Iraq.

17:48.634 --> 17:53.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Thirteen years after the U.S.
military invasion,
the country still struggles to
stand on its

17:53.739 --> 17:59.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
own, as it faces profound
challenges, none
more dire than the threat posed
by the Islamic

17:59.712 --> 18:02.181 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
State, which controls parts of
the country.

18:02.214 --> 18:06.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, in partnership with the
Pulitzer
Center on Crisis Reporting,
special correspondent

18:06.986 --> 18:12.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jane Ferguson and producer Jon
Gerberg look
at the coming crucial battle to
reclaim the

18:12.658 --> 18:17.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
city of Mosul from ISIS and to
drive it from
Iraq once and for all.

18:17.997 --> 18:25.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Hungry and
crushed together
in the punishing sun, these
Iraqis, refugees

18:25.037 --> 18:29.976 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in their own land, desperately
grasp for food.

18:30.009 --> 18:34.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have fled south of Mosul
City, where
fighting between government
forces and ISIS

18:34.513 --> 18:37.917 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
has been raging for months.

18:37.950 --> 18:43.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
New offensives have ISIS in
retreat, but with
their homes, and all they know,
engulfed in

18:43.990 --> 18:47.259 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the battle, they have come here.

18:47.293 --> 18:53.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Escaping from Mosul just days
ago, this woman
says she and her family of seven
were lucky

18:53.065 --> 18:54.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to get away.

18:54.834 --> 18:59.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Running away from ISIS is
dangerous, and she
didn't want to be identified.

18:59.238 --> 19:04.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator):
There are many
people who want to leave, but
cannot.

19:04.610 --> 19:06.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The ones they catch, they break
their legs.

19:06.846 --> 19:10.416 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They just use a block on the
sidewalk and
break their legs.

19:10.449 --> 19:14.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If the person has already gone
very far, they
just kill them.

19:14.086 --> 19:17.757 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: We are 60 miles
south of Mosul.

19:17.790 --> 19:22.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Just up the road, these troops
are fighting
the ISIS insurgency.

19:22.528 --> 19:27.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Iraqi special forces have
already pushed ISIS
from many areas of the country.

19:27.533 --> 19:33.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The battles have been tough,
destroying almost
everything in sight.

19:33.939 --> 19:39.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Iraqi army has fought for
months over
these areas south of Mosul City,
swathes of

19:39.712 --> 19:43.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
land and villages just like this
that they
have been pushed out of.

19:43.749 --> 19:49.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But even though they retook this
land several
months ago, civilians have yet
to return.

19:49.221 --> 19:55.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These soldiers now have their
sites set north,
planning to take back the city
of Mosul, the

19:55.127 --> 19:59.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Islamic State's last remaining
major urban
base in Iraq.

19:59.832 --> 20:05.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At 23, Mahmoud has fought and
won several
battles against the group.

20:05.237 --> 20:08.074 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And these men are ready to take
Mosul.

20:08.107 --> 20:12.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): By
God, my morale
is high.

20:12.344 --> 20:13.779 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Praise be to God.

20:13.813 --> 20:14.914 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Praise and thanks be to God.

20:14.947 --> 20:16.549 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We will kick is from Mosul.

20:16.582 --> 20:21.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: That confidence
is a major
turnaround from just two years
ago.

20:21.120 --> 20:27.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then, ISIS rushed into Iraq from
Syria and
swept down these very roads, as
the Iraqi

20:27.726 --> 20:30.429 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
army collapsed and ran away.

20:30.463 --> 20:34.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was a humiliating shock for
the country's
security forces.

20:34.733 --> 20:40.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ISIS declared their conquest a
new caliphate,
or Muslim empire, with the
capital based in

20:40.973 --> 20:45.511 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Raqqa, Syria, only 140 miles
from the border.

20:45.544 --> 20:50.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was from Mosul that the
group's leader,
Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi, first
appeared in public,

20:50.883 --> 20:57.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
preaching in the city's Grand
Mosque, demanding
obedience from Muslims around
the world.

20:57.289 --> 21:02.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For the past year, Iraq's
military has been
fighting back, retaking former
ISIS strongholds

21:03.028 --> 21:06.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of Fallujah and Ramadi.

21:06.098 --> 21:11.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now the Iraqi military is
planning a showdown
with ISIS in Mosul, a battle
they hope will

21:11.704 --> 21:14.540 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
push the group out of the
country.

21:14.573 --> 21:19.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iraqi special forces commander
General Maan
al-Saadi, believes is will soon
be on the

21:19.812 --> 21:21.614 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
run.

21:21.647 --> 21:23.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GENERAL MAAN AL-SAADI, Iraqi
Special Forces
Commander (through translator):
No one accepts

21:23.082 --> 21:25.384 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
them, whether civilian or
military.

21:25.417 --> 21:27.319 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We are living in the 21st
century.

21:27.353 --> 21:29.588 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Who would accept bloody savages
and killers?

21:29.622 --> 21:35.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Across Iraq, the
U.S. leads
a coalition of 19 countries
fighting ISIS,

21:35.561 --> 21:44.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but the push to retake Mosul
will be an Iraqi
military effort, with U.S.
military support.

21:44.103 --> 21:49.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
American airstrikes, guided by
the precision
of surveillance drones, have
already hammered

21:49.108 --> 21:51.410 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ISIS for more than two years.

21:51.443 --> 21:56.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Heavy vehicles, and attack
helicopters, designed
to press the fight on the
ground, can already

21:56.749 --> 21:59.285 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be seen on U.S. bases here.

21:59.318 --> 22:05.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And last week, the Pentagon
announced an additional
600 U.S. troops are heading to
Iraq, bringing

22:05.090 --> 22:10.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the number of American boots on
the ground
to more than 5,000.

22:10.262 --> 22:13.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the Americans will not be on
the front
lines.

22:13.432 --> 22:17.236 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That task falls to these regular
Iraqi troops.

22:17.269 --> 22:22.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have already fought ISIS in
other, smaller
cities, and now each soldier is
getting a

22:22.308 --> 22:30.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
month of extra training for the
tough door-to-door
urban warfare expected in Mosul.

22:30.649 --> 22:38.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It will be a huge test for these
men, with
Da'esh, as they call ISIS here,
likely to

22:38.123 --> 22:41.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
challenge their fighting skills
more than
ever before.

22:41.527 --> 22:47.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To prepare for the variety of
threats, roadside
bombs, booby traps, suicide car
bombs and

22:47.900 --> 22:55.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more, coalition partners from
the Australian
military are training these
young fighters.

22:55.874 --> 22:57.676 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have a clear, limited goal.

22:57.710 --> 22:59.511 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
COL.

22:59.545 --> 23:03.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW LOWE, Australian Army:
When you only
have four weeks of training,
it's important

23:03.115 --> 23:08.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to keep in the back of our minds
is that we
are not training them to be like
us.

23:08.887 --> 23:13.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are training them to be what
they need
to be to defeat Da'esh.

23:13.259 --> 23:19.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what we say in the training
role, amongst
the task group, is, make them
better than

23:19.632 --> 23:20.833 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Da'esh.

23:20.866 --> 23:23.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Iraqi soldiers
alone cannot
defeat ISIS.

23:23.902 --> 23:29.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The upcoming battle for Mosul
will involve
a complex mix of fighting
groups, some at

23:29.708 --> 23:31.744 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
odds with one another.

23:31.777 --> 23:37.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iranian-backed Shia militias,
like these currently
on the front line near Tikrit,
will be another

23:37.716 --> 23:41.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
fighting element.

23:41.687 --> 23:47.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Accused of taking orders from
Shiite commanders
in Tehran, they are blamed for
stirring sectarian

23:47.226 --> 23:49.895 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
tensions in Sunni areas.

23:49.928 --> 23:55.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mosul is a largely Sunni city,
and their participation
in the upcoming fight has been
politically

23:55.901 --> 23:58.570 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
divisive.

23:58.604 --> 24:07.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iran-backed fighters allied with
U.S.-backed
forces reflect the reality of
Iraq today.

24:07.313 --> 24:12.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are many players who have
found a common
goal in defeating ISIS, but it's
often the

24:12.484 --> 24:17.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
only thing uniting them.

24:17.323 --> 24:22.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Northern Iraq, Peshmerga
forces from the
semi-autonomous Kurdish region
near Mosul

24:22.494 --> 24:25.898 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will also play a role in the
fight for the
city.

24:25.931 --> 24:30.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have been at odds with the
Baghdad government
for decades, seeking
independence and a country

24:30.836 --> 24:32.271 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of their own.

24:32.304 --> 24:37.242 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They also see parts of Mosul as
rightly theirs.

24:37.276 --> 24:39.878 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This young Kurdish fighter told
us what motivates
him

24:39.912 --> 24:44.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEZAR ESMAEL MUSTAFA, Kurdish
Fighter (through
translator): This is for our
future, for the

24:44.149 --> 24:45.351 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
future of Kurdistan.

24:45.384 --> 24:48.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is an honor and we will give
our lives
for this cause.

24:48.487 --> 24:53.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: But the Kurdish
fighters, also
trained by and allied with the
U.S.-led coalition,

24:53.625 --> 24:56.929 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
don't want the Shia militias
joining the fight.

24:56.962 --> 25:01.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their spokesman told "PBS
NewsHour" plainly,
the Kurds do not approve.

25:01.266 --> 25:02.301 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
BRIG.

25:02.334 --> 25:04.136 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

25:04.169 --> 25:05.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HALGURD HIKMAT, ®MD-UL /Peshmerga
Spokesman
(through translator): The Shia
militias are

25:05.037 --> 25:06.438 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
foreigners to the people of that
area.

25:06.472 --> 25:08.874 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have no relations with the
land and the
people.

25:08.907 --> 25:12.044 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If they participate, they will
create conflict.

25:12.077 --> 25:17.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: This is where the
battle for
Mosul will begin.

25:17.282 --> 25:23.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Qayyarah, a small town just 35
miles south
of Mosul, was occupied by ISIS
until they

25:23.055 --> 25:25.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were pushed out just over a
month ago.

25:25.758 --> 25:29.094 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now some signs of life are
returning.

25:29.128 --> 25:34.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the entrance to the town, a
hand-painted
sign reads: "Here is Qayyarah,
the key to

25:34.433 --> 25:35.467 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
