problem-solver
by the independent group No
Labels, who I

30:36.234 --> 30:37.636 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have worked with.

30:37.669 --> 30:40.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Both are former
lawyers,
both known for their work ethic.

30:40.605 --> 30:42.340 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Neither is flashy.

30:42.374 --> 30:47.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Hassan charges Ayotte is too
conservative
for the state, in lockstep with
the GOP on

30:47.612 --> 30:51.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
defunding Planned Parenthood,
overturning
Roe vs. Wade, and on guns.

30:51.516 --> 30:53.351 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

30:53.385 --> 30:56.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAGGIE HASSAN: Whether it's
standing with
the gun lobby, rather than
expanding background

30:56.121 --> 31:00.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
checks so that terrorists can't
get guns online
and at gun shows, or whether
it's standing

31:00.325 --> 31:06.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
against a woman's right to make
her own health
care decisions, those decisions
of Senator

31:06.565 --> 31:11.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ayotte, her positions and her
votes, really
have pulled us backwards.

31:11.303 --> 31:17.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Ayotte stands
by her position
to ban most abortions as a
matter of faith,

31:17.642 --> 31:20.779 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
adding she supports access to
more contraception.

31:20.812 --> 31:24.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She attacks Hassan on taxes, a
core issue
here.

31:24.116 --> 31:25.951 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

31:25.984 --> 31:29.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KELLY AYOTTE: In terms of taxes,
I'm someone
who focuses on low taxes, a
better tax climate

31:29.488 --> 31:31.289 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for individuals and small
businesses.

31:31.323 --> 31:36.561 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
She has long record of
increasing taxes, not
only on small businesses, but on
campgrounds,

31:36.595 --> 31:39.498 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
registration fees on the people
of New Hampshire.

31:39.531 --> 31:43.135 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Hassan's tax
record is complicated.

31:43.168 --> 31:47.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She cut taxes for some, but
raised them for
others, citing urgent needs like
fighting

31:47.839 --> 31:49.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the opioid crisis.

31:49.841 --> 31:55.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meanwhile, both candidates are
keeping their
party's presidential nominees at
arm's length.

31:55.280 --> 31:59.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hillary Clinton and Donald Trump
were both
in New Hampshire last week, but
neither Hassan

31:59.885 --> 32:02.154 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
nor Ayotte joined them on stage.

32:02.187 --> 32:06.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ayotte has said she's voting for
Trump, but
not endorsing him.

32:06.892 --> 32:12.898 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But how do the important people,
the voters,
see this?

32:12.931 --> 32:18.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jim Jalbert runs a thriving
family-owned bus
company, C&amp;J Bus, in Portsmouth.

32:18.069 --> 32:22.374 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Jalbert is a registered
Republican who doesn't
like Trump.

32:22.407 --> 32:24.176 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But between Ayotte and Hassan:

32:24.209 --> 32:26.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JIM JALBERT, President, C&amp;J Bus:
If you look
at the two of them, they're both
really good

32:27.012 --> 32:27.979 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
people.

32:28.013 --> 32:30.515 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Jim has a lot
at stake.

32:30.549 --> 32:34.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's worried about passing on
his business
to a third generation, his sons.

32:34.619 --> 32:37.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's worried about taxes and
America's crumbling
roads.

32:37.823 --> 32:40.759 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JIM JALBERT: I don't vote for a
person based
on a single issue.

32:40.792 --> 32:43.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I vote for a person based on
what they're
going to do in total.

32:44.029 --> 32:50.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I look at the two of them,
and I think
that Ayotte, with her demeanor
and her style,

32:50.402 --> 32:52.270 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
will probably do more for New
Hampshire.

32:52.304 --> 32:57.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: But Hassan and
Democrats
would love a so-called Trump
drag on down-ballot

32:57.709 --> 33:00.712 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
races, especially in a place
like New Hampshire

33:00.745 --> 33:03.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Norm Ornstein of the American
Enterprise institute
explains.

33:03.381 --> 33:06.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NORMAN ORNSTEIN, Resident
Scholar, American
Enterprise Institute: If the
Democrats can't

33:06.084 --> 33:13.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
win in a purple state with a
large number
of highly educated voters who
are turned off

33:13.658 --> 33:19.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by Donald Trump, they're going
to have a much
more steeply uphill battle in
accomplishing

33:19.397 --> 33:20.765 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the goal of winning the Senate.

33:20.799 --> 33:24.436 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Let's look at
the Senate
battle map.

33:24.469 --> 33:29.107 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
To take over the Senate,
Democrats need to
gain four Senate seats if
Clinton is president

33:29.140 --> 33:34.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and her V.P. can break a tie, or
five seats
if Trump wins.

33:34.079 --> 33:36.214 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Democrats have a big advantage.

33:36.248 --> 33:39.117 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Look at the 10 most competitive
Senate seats.

33:39.150 --> 33:42.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Nine are red, held by
Republicans.

33:42.187 --> 33:45.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is Democrats' best chance
at a Senate
takeover?

33:45.323 --> 33:51.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, sources in both parties
believe they
will pick up Illinois and
Wisconsin.

33:51.229 --> 33:52.697 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That would be two.

33:52.731 --> 33:56.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In North Carolina and Missouri,
incumbent
Republicans are on the ropes.

33:56.401 --> 33:57.636 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
If they lose?

33:57.669 --> 34:01.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's two more Democratic
pick-ups, for four
total.

34:01.439 --> 34:07.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Democrats may lose Nevada,
or the presidency,
so they need to pick up at least
one more

34:07.712 --> 34:12.050 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
seat from a toss-up state like
New Hampshire.

34:12.083 --> 34:16.554 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That battle is playing out at
the 140-year-old
Deerfield Fair.

34:16.588 --> 34:20.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a jumble of food and
politics.

34:20.725 --> 34:25.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Andrew Robertson is splitting
his ticket,
voting Clinton for president,
but for Senate?

34:25.463 --> 34:30.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW ROBERTSON, New Hampshire:
yes, I think
I'm probably likely to vote for
Senator Ayotte,

34:30.101 --> 34:32.504 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in large part because of her
experience.

34:32.537 --> 34:34.339 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Others are an
equal mix.

34:34.372 --> 34:38.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAROL WYNNE, New Hampshire: I
really admire
Maggie Hassan.

34:38.376 --> 34:43.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She appears to have incredible
work ethic
and a great heart.

34:43.515 --> 34:46.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: Unenthusiastically, I am
supporting Ayotte.

34:46.551 --> 34:48.353 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Why
unenthusiastically?

34:48.386 --> 34:54.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: Well, basically because
Ayotte has not
been as supportive to the
Republican nominee

34:54.426 --> 34:56.161 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as she should be.

34:56.194 --> 34:59.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Enthusiastic
support from
the Senate will be key to
passing the next

34:59.831 --> 35:06.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
president's agenda, likely to
include several
Supreme Court nominations.

35:06.237 --> 35:08.073 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Norm Ornstein:

35:08.106 --> 35:12.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NORMAN ORNSTEIN: This year, I
really do believe
that the battle for control of
the Senate

35:12.444 --> 35:20.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is very close in importance to
that battle
for control of 1600 Pennsylvania
Avenue.

35:20.552 --> 35:25.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Those high
stakes have meant
sky-high spending here in the
Granite State,

35:25.190 --> 35:28.893 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and not just from the
candidates, but from
dozens of outside groups.

35:28.927 --> 35:33.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have flooded the airwaves
with tens of
millions of dollars in ads.

35:33.064 --> 35:36.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's in a state with just
over one million
people.

35:36.101 --> 35:40.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's by far the most spending
per person of
any Senate race.

35:40.672 --> 35:48.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ads from pro- and anti-gun
groups, from Planned
Parenthood, from big-money
groups on the left

35:48.079 --> 35:58.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and right all creating an
airwaves war, as
two popular candidates try to
outperform their

35:58.156 --> 36:02.027 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
parties' presidential nominees.

36:02.060 --> 36:06.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This makes voter contact, in
this retail politics
state, pivotal.

36:06.464 --> 36:12.404 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And, there, Ayotte has a
challenge: Usually,
Senate and presidential
campaigns coordinate,

36:12.437 --> 36:14.906 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but not so with Republicans this
year.

36:14.939 --> 36:18.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ayotte is on her own to identify
and get out
her voters.

36:18.777 --> 36:22.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All this means, right now, it's
any woman's
race.

36:22.280 --> 36:26.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour" I'm Lisa
Desjardins
in Portsmouth, New Hampshire.

36:26.651 --> 36:30.055 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: From the Senate
to the vice
presidential race.

36:30.088 --> 36:37.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
